body: Thanks Suresh, Selva. I'll check on T4/ODBC concern raised and create a separate JIRA if it is an issue.
Could we please have a JIRA that describes this problem?

A question (maybe I'll find the answer as I read the code): Is the replacement of WITH by a blockedUnion always done? Or is it a costed plan choice? I'm wondering what would happen if the WITH query was a simple scan with a highly selective key predicate for example. It might be faster to just scan it twice rather than scan it, write it to a temp table, then scan the temp table twice.
The changes look just right. Not sure why all those other commits show up in this pull request though. Probably harmless.

Good question about when the transformation is done. The plan is to have three values for CQD CSE_USE_TEMP: OFF, SYSTEM and ON. OFF and ON would do this transformation never or whenever possible. SYSTEM should decide based on heuristics. One of the reasons why the transformation happens in the semantic query optimization phase is that we can get some information on statistics to help us decide. I would like to leave the work on a heuristic decision to a future JIRA and deliver the code with just ON and OFF as choices.

In the even longer term, it would be good if we would make the decision in the optimizer, based on rules. Once we have that, I would hope that the SQO phase would heuristically decide the easy cases, and would leave some more difficult decisions to the optimizer.

See [TRAFODION-2315](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/TRAFODION-2315).

The spj has been updated to create an intermediate table for connectby

General steps:
There is an inner class Tuple in FileMgmt.java to instead of using arraylist in code.
1. Everytime running this SPJ it will drop old intermediate table(if exist) and then create new one.
2. SPJ get all nodes from source table and create an arraylist of tuples and convert it to adjacent table.
3. Based on the adjacent table we can using nested loops to get all paths ( so it will take long time if the source table is big)

usage
call qa_jdbc.connectbytable('intermediate_tbl','source_tbl','col_name','parent_col_name');
For instance(left is child and right is parent)
{ "0", "-1" },{ "1", "0" }, { "2", "0" }, { "3", "1" }, { "4", "1" },{ "5", "2" }, { "6", "2" }, { "7", "3" }, { "8", "3" }, { "9", "5" }, { "10", "3" }
the result is 
[(0,2), (0,6), (2,6), (0,5), (0,9), (2,5), (2,9), (5,9), (0,1), (0,4), (1,4), (0,3), (0,8), (1,3), (1,8), (3,8), (0,7), (1,7), (3,7), (0,10), (1,10), (3,10)]

This test is often a challenge to me, I question whether it provides any value for the tons of trouble it creates.

The test bundles several queries into a unit, then when we look at the aggregates we have no clue which query caused a change and whether that is a problem. It might be better to have a test that flags individual queries that change in their query cache status. Some day when we have lots of time to do this...
